The dataset has 55 total variables and 10,000 observations. The dataset is missing 7.7% of its cells. There are 19 categorical variables and 36 numerical variables.

Predictive Modeling

With the profiling, I was able to see that the interest_rate has a high correlation with grade, sub_grade, and paid_interest variables.

The linear model of the amount of interest paid so far and the current interest rate of the loan shows a positive relationship. As the paid interest increases by $1, the interest rate increases by 0.0049738%.

Cluster Analysis

featureset2 <- lender %>% select(interest_rate, paid_interest, total_debit_limit, debt_to_income_joint)
featureset2 <- na.omit(featureset2)

sil_width <- vector()
for (i in 2:10) {
    kms <- kmeans(featureset2, centers = i)
    sil <- silhouette(kms$cluster, dist(featureset2))
    sil_width[i] <- mean(sil[, 3])
}
ggplot() + geom_line(aes(x = 1:10, y = sil_width)) + scale_x_continuous(name = "k", 
    breaks = 1:10)
## Warning: Removed 1 row(s) containing missing values (geom_path).

# 2 clusters
pam1 <- featureset2 %>% pam(k = 2)
plot(pam1, which = 2, border = NA, col = "red")

featurePam <- featureset2 %>% pam(2)
featureset2 %>% mutate(cluster = as.factor(pam1$clustering)) %>% 
    ggpairs(aes(color = cluster), columnLabels = c("Interest Rate","Paid Interest","Debit Limit","Debt/Income", "Cluster"),
        upper = list(continuous = wrap('cor', size = 3)),
        title = "Scatterplot Matrix of Interest Rate Features") + 
  theme(axis.line=element_blank(),
        axis.text=element_blank(),
        axis.ticks=element_blank())

I wanted to determine if the numeric variables with correlation greater than .25 to interest rate had any interaction so I ran a cluster analysis; however, the average silhouette width was .61, meaning that the clusters were pretty weak.

Overall, if I had more time, I would run more regression prediction models on interest rate as well as investigate different variables for cluster analysis.

Visualizations

ggplot(lender, aes(x = total_debit_limit, y = interest_rate)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth() + labs(title = "Total Debit Limit vs Interest Rate", x = "Total Debit Limit", y = "Interest Rate") + scale_x_continuous(labels=scales::dollar_format())+ scale_y_continuous(labels=scales::percent_format(scale =1 ))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

For the third visualization, I noticed that total debit limit was negatively correlated with interest rate and I wanted to investigate the relationship further. It seems that as the total debit limit increases, the interest rate decreases exponentially; however, there is increased uncertainty past a total debit limit of $100,000 that averages around a 10% interest rate.

gradeIR <- featureSet %>% group_by(grade) %>% summarize(meanIR = mean(interest_rate))
ggplot(gradeIR, aes(x = grade, y = meanIR)) + geom_bar(stat = "identity", aes(fill = grade)) + labs(title = "Mean Interest Rate for Each Grade", x= "Grade", y = "Mean Interest Rate") +   geom_text(aes(label= format(round(meanIR, 2), nsmall = 2)), vjust=1.6, color="white", size=5) + scale_y_continuous(labels=scales::percent_format(scale = 1 )) + theme_minimal()

For fourth visualization, I investigated the mean interest rate per grade.

plot_usmap(data = lender, values = "interest_rate", color = "blue") + scale_fill_continuous(low = "white", high = "blue", name = "Interest Rates", label = scales::percent_format(scale =1 )) +
  labs(title = "US Map of Interest Rates") + theme(legend.position = "right")
